\begin{abstract}
    One of the most common ways people are exposed to mathematics are through
    the visually pleasing mathematical objects.  The aim of this article is to
    use algebraic surfaces to highlight interesting areas of mathematics, and
    hopefully provide a way people easily can dive in and visualize these
    themselves. We take a look at the mathematical definition of algebraic
    surfaces. We then consider their singularities, how to remove their
    singularities, and the symmetries of such singularities. 
\end{abstract}
\tableofcontents

\section{Algebraic Surfaces}
\label{sec:algebraic_surfaces}

In order to understand mathematically what kind of object we are dealing with,
namely the algebraic surfaces, we must first introduce some preliminaries.
Starting with the notion of an \emph{algebraic variety\index{algebraic
variety}}.
\begin{defn}[Affine Algebraic Variety]
    Given a ring of polynomials in $n$ variables $k \left[ x_1, \ldots, x_n
    \right]$ where $k$ is an algebraically closed field, let $S \subset k
    \left[ x_1, \ldots, x_n \right]$ be a set of polynomials. We define the
    \emph{affine algebraic variety associated to $S$} as the set of solutions
        \begin{equation}
            \notag
            V(S) = \left\{x \in k^n \mid f(x) = 0 \text{ for all } f \in S \right\}.
        \end{equation}
\end{defn}
This definition might seem a bit cryptic, but we can give a fairly intuitive
example.
\begin{exm}[Roots of unity]
    Let $k = \C$ and $S = \left\{ f_n(z) = z^n + 1 \mid n \in \N \right\}$ then
    the algebraic variety associated to $S$ will be the roots of unity on the
    circle in the complex plane.
\end{exm}

One of the distinguishing features between a \emph{manifold} and an algebraic
variety is that the algebraic varieties may exhibit singularities. This is one
of the more aesthetically pleasing properties of algebraic surfaces, hence
something we are very much interested in. A singularity is strictly speaking a
point where the surface and the partial derivatives vanish identically. We
define this formally:

\begin{defn}[Point of Singularity \protect{\cite{OLabs2}} \index{singularity}]
    A point $p$ in $\C^n$ is called a \emph{singular point} or
    \emph{singularity of the hypersurface} $f \in \C \left[ x_1, \ldots, x_n
    \right]$ if $f(p) = 0$ and all the partial derivatives are zero.
    Mathematically:
    \begin{equation}
        \notag
        \party{{}}{x_i}f(p) = 0 \quad \text{ for all } \quad i = 1, \ldots, n.
    \end{equation}
\end{defn}

Again, we can give a few examples. 
\begin{exm}
    Let our surface of degree $2$ be defined by $f(x) = ax^2 + by^2 + cz^2 + d
    = 0$. We first take the look at the partial derivatives. These are given by
    \begin{align*}
        \party{f}{x} = 2ax = 0, && \party{f}{y} = 2by = 0, && \party{f}{z} = 2cz = 0.
    \end{align*}
\end{exm}

